00:36:30.920 --> 00:36:32.420
is actually what
we normally do when

00:36:32.420 --> 00:36:34.461
I go in and do corporate
training and consulting.

00:36:34.461 --> 00:36:37.460
So you've given me a nice
little transition here.

00:36:37.460 --> 00:36:40.730
So we have something we call the
aligned leadership model, which

00:36:40.730 --> 00:36:43.430
is a model that actually
has what we would consider

00:36:43.430 --> 00:36:45.650
to be like more feminine
qualities of leadership

00:36:45.650 --> 00:36:46.340
attached to it.

00:36:46.340 --> 00:36:48.620
It is fundamentally an
emotionally intelligent model

00:36:48.620 --> 00:36:49.402
of leadership.

00:36:49.402 --> 00:36:51.860
And it starts from the place
of thinking through leadership

00:36:51.860 --> 00:36:52.679
from--

00:36:52.679 --> 00:36:54.470
I mean, there's 12
points on a pivot wheel.

00:36:54.470 --> 00:36:56.520
It would take me a whole
other hour to go through it.

00:36:56.520 --> 00:36:58.010
But fundamentally it
starts from a place

00:36:58.010 --> 00:37:00.320
of the most effective leadership
in today's environment

00:37:00.320 --> 00:37:03.890
being leadership that starts
with curiosity and compassion.

00:37:03.890 --> 00:37:07.040
And so it's not,
I am the King, I'm

00:37:07.040 --> 00:37:09.740
the ultimate know it all of
how this company should run.

00:37:09.740 --> 00:37:12.920
But really, more of a
questioning, a consistent

00:37:12.920 --> 00:37:15.380
questioning of how
can we improve?

00:37:15.380 --> 00:37:16.560
What am I good at?

00:37:16.560 --> 00:37:17.889
What is my team good at?

00:37:17.889 --> 00:37:20.180
How can I look at what my
gifts are and where I'm weak,

00:37:20.180 --> 00:37:22.830
and build an organization
that fills in the gaps?

00:37:22.830 --> 00:37:25.940
How can I value everyone's
gifts on my team, right?

00:37:25.940 --> 00:37:28.340
And it also talks
through the concept

00:37:28.340 --> 00:37:30.710
that I shared with you
today of growth as one

00:37:30.710 --> 00:37:33.510
of the main metrics of success.

00:37:33.510 --> 00:37:36.050
So to me, I wouldn't
want to call it

00:37:36.050 --> 00:37:37.460
a feminine model of leadership.

00:37:37.460 --> 00:37:39.580
I think it's-- I think
it's far more healthy.

00:37:39.580 --> 00:37:40.100
Right?

00:37:40.100 --> 00:37:41.960
Our aligned leadership
model that we teach

00:37:41.960 --> 00:37:44.600
is really about, how do you
create healthy ecosystems

00:37:44.600 --> 00:37:46.730
inside companies where
everyone is functional

00:37:46.730 --> 00:37:50.530
and, moreover, that is
holistic, so that it's not just

00:37:50.530 --> 00:37:52.280
about what the person
can perform at work.

00:37:52.280 --> 00:37:54.070
I mean, you guys are
amazing in here, by the way.

00:37:54.070 --> 00:37:56.153
I have to say that of all
the working environments

00:37:56.153 --> 00:37:57.920
that I've stepped
into, this one seems

00:37:57.920 --> 00:38:00.890
to care the most about the
totality of the human beings

00:38:00.890 --> 00:38:01.560
who work here.

00:38:01.560 --> 00:38:05.180
And that is amazing to
me, and truly something

00:38:05.180 --> 00:38:08.330
to be honored and
admired and uplifted.

00:38:08.330 --> 00:38:11.424
But so many environments that I
walk into only care about what

00:38:11.424 --> 00:38:13.340
happens to the individual
in terms of how they

00:38:13.340 --> 00:38:15.380
can provide for the company.

00:38:15.380 --> 00:38:15.881
Right?

00:38:15.881 --> 00:38:17.713
And how they can perform
when they're there.

00:38:17.713 --> 00:38:19.190
And if somebody's
spouse is dying,

00:38:19.190 --> 00:38:21.740
or someone's child is
having a crisis, who

00:38:21.740 --> 00:38:25.610
cares as long as the
bottom line needs are met?

00:38:25.610 --> 00:38:27.290
Aligned leadership,
to me, is really

00:38:27.290 --> 00:38:29.955
about recognizing that
we're all connected.

00:38:29.955 --> 00:38:32.330
That organizations are only
as healthy as the individuals

00:38:32.330 --> 00:38:33.500
who are within them.

00:38:33.500 --> 00:38:36.440
And that just in the
same way that each of us

00:38:36.440 --> 00:38:38.930
have gifts to
contribute to the world,

00:38:38.930 --> 00:38:40.350
organizations do as well.

00:38:40.350 --> 00:38:42.680
And so mission is really
critical and important,

00:38:42.680 --> 00:38:44.990
and making decisions
based on mission

00:38:44.990 --> 00:38:47.630
that are aligned with
also all the individuals

00:38:47.630 --> 00:38:50.390
that make up that mission
creates environments

00:38:50.390 --> 00:38:52.870
that people want to live in,
and work in, and are loyal to,

00:38:52.870 --> 00:38:54.560
and that you can't
imagine leaving.

00:38:54.560 --> 00:38:56.107
And just having
talked to some of you

00:38:56.107 --> 00:38:58.190
today as I was walking
around before here, I mean,

00:38:58.190 --> 00:38:59.450
that's very present here.

00:38:59.450 --> 00:39:00.170
Right?

00:39:00.170 --> 00:39:02.090
That degree of respect
and understanding

00:39:02.090 --> 00:39:04.560
of the way in which everybody
who works here is connected

00:39:04.560 --> 00:39:06.060
and the needs of
everyone being met.

00:39:06.060 --> 00:39:08.060
So that to me is
about as close as I

00:39:08.060 --> 00:39:10.244
can get without doing
like a full blown all day

00:39:10.244 --> 00:39:12.660
long training like I normally
do in corporate environments

00:39:12.660 --> 00:39:14.240
like this.

00:39:14.240 --> 00:39:16.392
But yeah, it really is
about emotional intelligence

00:39:16.392 --> 00:39:17.600
fundamentally as a principle.

00:39:17.600 --> 00:39:19.280
And then mission and
purpose and making

00:39:19.280 --> 00:39:21.530
all of your decisions about
your people and the people

00:39:21.530 --> 00:39:23.450
who work for you as
if we're a family.

00:39:23.450 --> 00:39:24.520
Because we are.

00:39:24.520 --> 00:39:25.310
Right?

00:39:25.310 --> 00:39:26.680
Make sense?

