MCLAUGHLIN: Well so if
they've been erased,

00:39:37.610 --> 00:39:38.943
you have to do a lot of digging.

00:39:38.943 --> 00:39:42.560
So I would tell a story
about this that's kind of--

00:39:42.560 --> 00:39:44.280
that really brought
this home to me.

00:39:44.280 --> 00:39:45.738
But I will tell
you that it took me

00:39:45.738 --> 00:39:48.330
about three hours of like
serious, serious digging

00:39:48.330 --> 00:39:51.670
on the internet to find anything
that remotely looked like.

00:39:51.670 --> 00:39:55.710
So my maiden name is
Cronise, as you all know.

00:39:55.710 --> 00:39:58.090
And my father is
really into ancestry.

00:39:58.090 --> 00:39:59.940
So one of the things
that we discovered

00:39:59.940 --> 00:40:02.555
when he did all of this
work is that our family

00:40:02.555 --> 00:40:03.930
on my father's
side is originally

00:40:03.930 --> 00:40:04.920
from Alsace-Lorraine.

00:40:04.920 --> 00:40:09.000
And the spelling of our
name originally in German

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:10.860
means iron crown.

00:40:10.860 --> 00:40:13.110
And so I went digging
because my father was--

00:40:13.110 --> 00:40:15.420
we were ironworkers apparently
and the 15th century.

00:40:15.420 --> 00:40:16.890
You know, my dad's gone all
the way back through all this.

00:40:16.890 --> 00:40:19.260
But I went digging to see,
well, what's the reference

00:40:19.260 --> 00:40:21.030
point for this name?

00:40:21.030 --> 00:40:23.760
I discovered in like
three hours of kind

00:40:23.760 --> 00:40:25.510
of falling down a rabbit hole--

00:40:25.510 --> 00:40:29.100
this is the old lawyer
in me, the researcher--

00:40:29.100 --> 00:40:31.860
that there was this thing
called the iron crown.

00:40:31.860 --> 00:40:34.020
Some of you may
know historically.

00:40:34.020 --> 00:40:36.060
But the iron crown
was originally

00:40:36.060 --> 00:40:41.972
commissioned by a queen in the
third century whose name I'm

00:40:41.972 --> 00:40:43.680
now going to forget
because nobody's ever

00:40:43.680 --> 00:40:45.840
heard of her because the history
has been completely erased.

00:40:45.840 --> 00:40:47.050
But I did a whole podcast.

00:40:47.050 --> 00:40:49.425
I run this podcast called The
Women's Leadership Podcast.

00:40:49.425 --> 00:40:51.530
I did a podcast on
just this experience

00:40:51.530 --> 00:40:54.060
of recognizing that there had
been a woman who basically had

00:40:54.060 --> 00:40:58.260
been the head of something
the size of the Ottoman Empire

00:40:58.260 --> 00:41:00.990
at some point in our history
that none of us know about.

00:41:00.990 --> 00:41:02.850
Like I literally had
not heard of this woman

00:41:02.850 --> 00:41:04.891
ever before until I went
digging for all of this,

00:41:04.891 --> 00:41:07.230
because the stories that
we are taught about history

00:41:07.230 --> 00:41:08.633
are the stories of men.

00:41:08.633 --> 00:41:11.132
And so to some extent it's about
your degree of-- we're back

00:41:11.132 --> 00:41:12.120
to curiosity again--

00:41:12.120 --> 00:41:14.790
your degree of curiosity
about women's history.

00:41:14.790 --> 00:41:16.950
And to some extent, it's
also about recognizing

00:41:16.950 --> 00:41:20.130
that many of our traditions have
always been oral traditions.

00:41:20.130 --> 00:41:21.810
And so this is one
of the reasons why

00:41:21.810 --> 00:41:23.830
women's storytelling
still is really important,

00:41:23.830 --> 00:41:25.664
and one of the reasons
why I encourage women

00:41:25.664 --> 00:41:28.204
who want to know about even the
history of their own families

00:41:28.204 --> 00:41:30.570
to go into their grandmothers
on tape before they die.

00:41:30.570 --> 00:41:32.490
Because otherwise it
gets lost if it's not

00:41:32.490 --> 00:41:33.448
written down somewhere.

00:41:33.448 --> 00:41:35.490
So I wish I could
say that there was

00:41:35.490 --> 00:41:38.190
like a magic
un-eraser button that

00:41:38.190 --> 00:41:40.380
would bring all of this
back, but I think some of it

00:41:40.380 --> 00:41:43.130
has to be about how far
are you as an individual

00:41:43.130 --> 00:41:45.820
willing to do the dig, to then
share it with the collective.

00:41:45.820 --> 00:41:47.820
I mean, this is a great
opportunity, by the way,

00:41:47.820 --> 00:41:48.450
for a project.

00:41:48.450 --> 00:41:50.741
Like somebody should start
a reclaiming women's history

00:41:50.741 --> 00:41:52.410
project, if it's
not done already,

00:41:52.410 --> 00:41:56.440
just so that we can start to
see like all the gaps there.

00:41:56.440 --> 00:41:57.450
Yeah.

00:41:57.450 --> 00:41:59.400
So that's my answer to that.

00:41:59.400 --> 00:42:02.520
Individual choice, I
think, at this point.

00:42:02.520 --> 00:42:08.880
AUDIENCE: So I am lucky to
be in a leadership position,

00:42:08.880 --> 00:42:13.470
and I have a team that
has one other woman on it

00:42:13.470 --> 00:42:14.760
and the rest are men.

00:42:14.760 --> 00:42:17.010
And the team that I
lead are generally

00:42:17.010 --> 00:42:21.330
somewhere in the range of about
15 years behind me career-wise.

00:42:21.330 --> 00:42:27.330
And what I've tried to
do is to adapt my style

00:42:27.330 --> 00:42:29.190
to the needs of each
person on the team,

00:42:29.190 --> 00:42:30.810
because they are very different.

00:42:30.810 --> 00:42:33.480
Their experiences are different,
their communication styles

00:42:33.480 --> 00:42:35.340
are different.

00:42:35.340 --> 00:42:40.440
And try to give that
hand up to all of them.

00:42:40.440 --> 00:42:43.530
And what I have found
in the last year or two

00:42:43.530 --> 00:42:47.730
is that I sometimes
have people call me

00:42:47.730 --> 00:42:51.930
out as favoring the
woman on the team

00:42:51.930 --> 00:42:55.080
even though when I sit down
and talk to them about all

00:42:55.080 --> 00:42:59.160
of the ways that I'm investing
in their careers and the things

00:42:59.160 --> 00:43:02.340
that I'm doing for them,
they recognize that they're

00:43:02.340 --> 00:43:04.530
getting as much or more.

00:43:04.530 --> 00:43:06.030
And so you know,
as you were talking

00:43:06.030 --> 00:43:11.220
about our responsibility of
kind of bringing up other women,

00:43:11.220 --> 00:43:15.322
you know, what about the people
who stand on the sidelines

00:43:15.322 --> 00:43:17.280
and go, well see, you're
just playing favorites

00:43:17.280 --> 00:43:18.280
and that's just no better?

00:43:18.280 --> 00:43:18.980
ELIZABETH CRONISE
MCLAUGHLIN: Right.

00:43:18.980 --> 00:43:20.070
Right.

00:43:20.070 --> 00:43:21.962
So it's hard to
give up privilege.

00:43:21.962 --> 00:43:24.420
You know, as I said, it's really
hard to give up privilege.

00:43:24.420 --> 00:43:27.840
And some of what the
communication that we all need

00:43:27.840 --> 00:43:33.360
to learn, I think, to do
better is also to say equity

00:43:33.360 --> 00:43:34.770
is not about playing favorites.

00:43:34.770 --> 00:43:35.280
Right?

00:43:35.280 --> 00:43:37.740
Meaning that, and
the image that I

00:43:37.740 --> 00:43:39.780
share with people about
equity versus equality

00:43:39.780 --> 00:43:42.439
is that in order to reach
true equity culturally,

00:43:42.439 --> 00:43:44.730
you do have to lift up people
who historically have not

00:43:44.730 --> 00:43:46.590
had the extra lift.

00:43:46.590 --> 00:43:47.130
Right?

00:43:47.130 --> 00:43:50.260
It's like, think about
it from this perspective.

00:43:50.260 --> 00:43:52.950
The image that I've seen on
this that's so descriptive

00:43:52.950 --> 00:43:55.320
is you've got people at
three different heights

00:43:55.320 --> 00:43:56.190
behind the fence.

00:43:56.190 --> 00:43:56.847
Right?

00:43:56.847 --> 00:43:58.680
And equality is that
everybody gets to stand

00:43:58.680 --> 00:44:00.220
at the same place on the fence.

00:44:00.220 --> 00:44:02.430
Equity is that everybody
can see over it.

00:44:02.430 --> 00:44:02.970
Right?

00:44:02.970 --> 00:44:06.170
And so sometimes that means that
from a historic perspective,

00:44:06.170 --> 00:44:07.860
you have to do
things differently

00:44:07.860 --> 00:44:09.030
in order to create equity.

00:44:09.030 --> 00:44:10.170
There will be a
point, hopefully,

00:44:10.170 --> 00:44:12.044
in the future where we
don't have to do that.

00:44:12.044 --> 00:44:15.000
But to me, first of all,
that's not playing favorites

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:16.410
so I wouldn't call it that.

00:44:16.410 --> 00:44:17.010
I guess that's the thing.

00:44:17.010 --> 00:44:18.690
You can shout it out
and say, actually

00:44:18.690 --> 00:44:19.610
that's not what I'm doing.

00:44:19.610 --> 00:44:20.970
And do what you're
already doing there,

00:44:20.970 --> 00:44:22.636
which I think it sound
like, I hope it's

00:44:22.636 --> 00:44:24.750
working to a certain extent.

00:44:24.750 --> 00:44:26.430
But the flip side
of that as well

00:44:26.430 --> 00:44:29.016
is that if we do
not actually start

00:44:29.016 --> 00:44:31.140
to make different choices
in corporate environments

00:44:31.140 --> 00:44:33.200
as leaders, nothing shifts.

00:44:33.200 --> 00:44:33.890
Right?

00:44:33.890 --> 00:44:36.300
Like my biggest client is a
publicly traded investment

00:44:36.300 --> 00:44:37.590
bank.

00:44:37.590 --> 00:44:41.130
And they discovered-- they
did some research last year

00:44:41.130 --> 00:44:44.700
and they discovered that only
4.7% of their senior executives

00:44:44.700 --> 00:44:49.265
are women, even though
they hire 35% as women.

00:44:49.265 --> 00:44:51.390
And they're losing people
and they've never kind of

00:44:51.390 --> 00:44:52.260
investigated why.

00:44:52.260 --> 00:44:54.814
Which is crazy to me, but
they're never looked at it.

00:44:54.814 --> 00:44:56.730
One of the things that
I've had to say to them

00:44:56.730 --> 00:44:59.280
is, why are you not recruiting
at historically women's

00:44:59.280 --> 00:45:00.000
colleges?

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:00.570
Right?

00:45:00.570 --> 00:45:02.761
Why are you not thinking
about maybe the fact

00:45:02.761 --> 00:45:05.010
that you need to provide
different kinds of leadership

00:45:05.010 --> 00:45:07.530
training for women so that
they understand how to navigate

00:45:07.530 --> 00:45:08.700
this environment better?

00:45:08.700 --> 00:45:11.080
Why are your senior male
leaders not signing on

00:45:11.080 --> 00:45:14.640
to initiatives that say,
we're making a commitment

00:45:14.640 --> 00:45:16.680
as an organization
to gender parity,

00:45:16.680 --> 00:45:17.940
and here's what we're
willing to do about it.

00:45:17.940 --> 00:45:19.830
Here's the investment that
we're willing to make,

00:45:19.830 --> 00:45:22.163
here's the training programs
that we want to ascribe to.

00:45:22.163 --> 00:45:24.330
Because the other thing
is that the unfortunate

00:45:24.330 --> 00:45:27.090
thing about being a woman leader
right now in some environments

00:45:27.090 --> 00:45:29.640
is that you have to do the
emotional labor of educating

00:45:29.640 --> 00:45:32.770
people about what it is
that needs to change.

00:45:32.770 --> 00:45:35.550
And it is so much easier
if senior male leaders also

00:45:35.550 --> 00:45:38.970
sign onto that as allies
so that the messaging comes

00:45:38.970 --> 00:45:39.760
from other men.

00:45:39.760 --> 00:45:40.260
Right?

00:45:40.260 --> 00:45:42.340
We're back to this issue of
how can you kind of like--

00:45:42.340 --> 00:45:44.520
how can other men work as
allies to educate other men

00:45:44.520 --> 00:45:46.144
about the benefits
of what's happening?

00:45:46.144 --> 00:45:48.000
So I don't know.

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:50.250
I don't want to tell you
what all the solutions should

00:45:50.250 --> 00:45:52.140
be for you, but it
does sound to me

00:45:52.140 --> 00:45:55.050
like you need some male allies
as well on this front who

00:45:55.050 --> 00:45:58.800
can communicate this to your
team in ways that make sense,

00:45:58.800 --> 00:46:00.810
so that you're not the
one that is bearing

00:46:00.810 --> 00:46:03.480
the burden of doing
the right thing

00:46:03.480 --> 00:46:06.510
and having them feel
like that's unfair.

00:46:06.510 --> 00:46:07.355
Helpful?

00:46:07.355 --> 00:46:07.980
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:46:07.980 --> 00:46:08.730
And it was more--

00:46:08.730 --> 00:46:11.830
I mean, I feel like on our team,
we have very good communication

00:46:11.830 --> 00:46:15.540
and we talked through this and
everybody's on the same page.

00:46:15.540 --> 00:46:18.510
But as I look around and
you use that analogy of kind

00:46:18.510 --> 00:46:20.820
of giving a hand
up to other women,

00:46:20.820 --> 00:46:23.730
it is something that everybody
kind of has to think through

00:46:23.730 --> 00:46:26.160
in terms of, is this
going to be misperceived

00:46:26.160 --> 00:46:28.320
as preferential treatment?

00:46:28.320 --> 00:46:30.000
Or what's the best
way to communicate

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:31.020
that it isn't really?

00:46:31.020 --> 00:46:32.640
And I think you did a
good job of covering that.

00:46:32.640 --> 00:46:33.050
Thank you.

00:46:33.050 --> 00:46:33.477
ELIZABETH CRONISE
MCLAUGHLIN: Yeah.

00:46:33.477 --> 00:46:34.760
You're welcome.

00:46:34.760 --> 00:46:35.700
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:46:35.700 --> 00:46:37.700
I wanted to get your
thoughts on this situation.

00:46:37.700 --> 00:46:41.060
It's not happening in this
company, another company,

00:46:41.060 --> 00:46:42.320
to a friend of mine.

00:46:42.320 --> 00:46:46.250
She wanted to switch teams
within the same company, had

00:46:46.250 --> 00:46:48.380
an offer with another team.

00:46:48.380 --> 00:46:49.660
She was pregnant.

00:46:49.660 --> 00:46:52.556
A few weeks before
her delivery, she

00:46:52.556 --> 00:46:55.100
talks to the manager,
a new manager,

00:46:55.100 --> 00:46:58.010
is offered this position.

00:46:58.010 --> 00:47:00.020
She plays the devil's
advocate, saying

00:47:00.020 --> 00:47:02.480
hey I'm going to be
gone a few months.

00:47:02.480 --> 00:47:04.610
I totally understand
that, was the response.

00:47:04.610 --> 00:47:06.950
We still want you here,
we value you here.

00:47:06.950 --> 00:47:09.200
Baby is born, it's
been two months now.

00:47:09.200 --> 00:47:11.870
Now she gets a call
saying, we think

00:47:11.870 --> 00:47:14.590
this position is no
longer a great fit,

00:47:14.590 --> 00:47:17.600
we are not sure we
would value you as much.

00:47:17.600 --> 00:47:20.100
It's a pretty reputed company,
I can't tell you which it is.

00:47:20.100 --> 00:47:22.130
A very close friend of mine.

00:47:22.130 --> 00:47:24.050
I'm angry.

00:47:24.050 --> 00:47:26.649
And the manager
talks to her saying,

00:47:26.649 --> 00:47:28.940
I want to grow the people
who are currently in the team

00:47:28.940 --> 00:47:30.622
to be the manager.

00:47:30.622 --> 00:47:32.830
Well nothing's changed, her
pregnancy hasn't changed,

00:47:32.830 --> 00:47:34.980
the same people continue
to be in the team.

00:47:34.980 --> 00:47:37.020
Now there's suddenly a question.

00:47:37.020 --> 00:47:38.780
Now the way she's
responding is she's

00:47:38.780 --> 00:47:40.988
being the mentoring role
for this manager and saying,

00:47:40.988 --> 00:47:43.850
hey, do what's
right for the team.

00:47:43.850 --> 00:47:45.770
So business-wise, the
right thing for the team

00:47:45.770 --> 00:47:47.660
is not to wait for a
couple of more months

00:47:47.660 --> 00:47:49.890
for her to get done back?

00:47:49.890 --> 00:47:51.515
And which is what is
likely the manager

00:47:51.515 --> 00:47:53.810
is hoping to hear from her.

00:47:53.810 --> 00:47:55.670
And I don't want her
to be in a position

00:47:55.670 --> 00:47:59.060
where she's no longer
going to be as much valued.

00:47:59.060 --> 00:48:01.849
The other options
are, we create one--

00:48:01.849 --> 00:48:03.390
we'll create a new
opportunity that's

00:48:03.390 --> 00:48:05.587
like one third of what
you were supposed to own.

00:48:05.587 --> 00:48:07.670
It doesn't make sense from
owning the whole thing,

00:48:07.670 --> 00:48:09.540
why would I go back
to owning a third?

00:48:09.540 --> 00:48:11.690
This is a big corporation here.

00:48:11.690 --> 00:48:14.150
I don't want her to fight
against this corporation.

00:48:14.150 --> 00:48:17.430
Her career would be
ruined after this.

00:48:17.430 --> 00:48:18.980
And so she--

00:48:18.980 --> 00:48:22.300
I mean, if you just wear the
business hat, it feels like,

00:48:22.300 --> 00:48:24.830
yeah the manager made a
stupid mistake probably

00:48:24.830 --> 00:48:26.330
to offer her a job
and she's going

00:48:26.330 --> 00:48:27.450
to disappear in a few months.

00:48:27.450 --> 00:48:29.533
But I was happy that he
did thinking the long term

00:48:29.533 --> 00:48:32.700
potential and the
long term value.

00:48:32.700 --> 00:48:34.100
What do you typically recommend?

00:48:34.100 --> 00:48:35.990
I'm sure this is just
one of many instances

00:48:35.990 --> 00:48:37.820
that are happening
out there today.

00:48:37.820 --> 00:48:38.450
ELIZABETH CRONISE
MCLAUGHLIN: It's true.

00:48:38.450 --> 00:48:39.874
You know, I have
to say that it's

00:48:39.874 --> 00:48:42.290
really unfortunate because I
hear stories like this a lot.

00:48:42.290 --> 00:48:45.530
Pregnancy discrimination
is still very real.

00:48:45.530 --> 00:48:47.800
To the point where when I'm
coaching women leaders one

00:48:47.800 --> 00:48:49.970
on one, we have conversations
proactively when

00:48:49.970 --> 00:48:52.604
they want to even get pregnant
about how they have to prepare

00:48:52.604 --> 00:48:54.020
their team for
that, how they have

00:48:54.020 --> 00:48:56.630
to prepare their senior
leadership for it,

00:48:56.630 --> 00:48:57.620
how to disclose it.

00:48:57.620 --> 00:48:58.820
Women I coached through
job transitions,

00:48:58.820 --> 00:49:00.903
like, when do I tell people
I'm pregnant while I'm

00:49:00.903 --> 00:49:01.850
interviewing?

00:49:01.850 --> 00:49:04.010
These are all incredibly
difficult questions

00:49:04.010 --> 00:49:05.570
that we still have
to think about.

00:49:05.570 --> 00:49:06.680
Which is crazy to me.

00:49:06.680 --> 00:49:09.630
But all that said, for
your friend's situation,

00:49:09.630 --> 00:49:12.560
you know, I guess
the lawyer in me

00:49:12.560 --> 00:49:15.800
initially says she couldn't
find a good employment lawyer

00:49:15.800 --> 00:49:19.550
and actually ask some questions
about what the strategy there

00:49:19.550 --> 00:49:21.039
has to be from a
legal standpoint.

00:49:21.039 --> 00:49:22.580
And I know you don't
want her to sue,

00:49:22.580 --> 00:49:24.350
but I will tell you
that the employment

00:49:24.350 --> 00:49:28.520
lawyers that my company refers
our clients to help people

00:49:28.520 --> 00:49:31.370
negotiate situations
like this so

00:49:31.370 --> 00:49:32.810
that they walk the edge of it.

00:49:32.810 --> 00:49:35.990
Meaning that, that manager
knows that he's doing something

00:49:35.990 --> 00:49:37.170
that's not quite right.

00:49:37.170 --> 00:49:38.240
You know, I mean
it's obvious, or he

00:49:38.240 --> 00:49:39.260
wouldn't be having
the conversation

00:49:39.260 --> 00:49:40.610
the way that he's having it.

00:49:40.610 --> 00:49:43.259
If she is able to come back
with something that says,

00:49:43.259 --> 00:49:45.050
you made me this offer
when I was pregnant,

00:49:45.050 --> 00:49:45.900
you knew that I was pregnant.

00:49:45.900 --> 00:49:47.490
I understand you now
want to grow the team,

00:49:47.490 --> 00:49:49.198
but this is the offer
